{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}} {{short description|Thai Buddhist monk}} {{good article}} {{Infobox religious biography | background = #FFD068 | name = Dhammajayo | image=Luang Por Dhammajayo.jpg | caption =Luang Por Dhammajayo, taken in the old section of [[Wat Phra Dhammakaya]] | alias = | dharma name = Dhammajayo | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1944|4|22|df=yes}} | birth_place = [[Sing Buri Province]] | death_date = | death_place = | nationality = [[Thailand|Thai]] | religion = [[Buddhism]] | school = [[Theravada]], [[Maha Nikaya]] | lineage = [[Wat Paknam Bhasicharoen]] | title = Honorary Abbot of [[Wat Phra Dhammakaya]] | location = [[Wat Phra Dhammakaya]], [[Pathum Thani]], [[Thailand]] | education = | teacher = [[Luang Pu Sodh Candasaro]], [[Chandra Khonnokyoong]] | reincarnation of = | predecessor = | successor = | students = | spouse = | children = | website = [http://en.dhammakaya.net/about/the-dhammakaya-masters/ Biography of Luang Por Dhammajayo] }} '''Luang Por Dhammajayo''' ({{lang-th|ธมฺมชโย}}, {{rtgs|''Thammachayo''}}, ''[[Luang Por]]'' being a deferential title), also known by the lay name '''Chaiyabun Suddhipol''', is a Thai Buddhist monk. He was the abbot of the Buddhist temple [[Wat Phra Dhammakaya]], the post he held until 1999 and again from 2006 to December 2011. In December 2016, he was given the post of honorary abbot of the temple. He is a student of the nun (''[[maechi]]'') [[Chandra Khonnokyoong]], and is the most well-known teacher of [[Dhammakaya meditation]].<ref name="Times Asia article">{{cite news|url=http://content.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,2053923,00.html|title=Trouble in Nirvana|last1=Liebhold|first1=David|date=28 June 1999|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|accessdate=10 November 2016|last2=Horn|first2=Robert}}</ref> He has been subject to heavy criticism and some government response. However, he continues to be a spiritual leader that has significant influence in Thai society.{{sfn|McDaniel|2006|p=110}} Luang Por Dhammajayo's approach to Buddhism seeks to combine the ascetic and meditative life with modern personal ethics and social prosperity.
Luang Por Dhammajayo met Maechi Chandra in his student years, and learnt about Buddhism from her. During his student years, he met his fellow student who later became known as [[Luang Por Dattajivo]]. Luang Por Dhammajayo started teaching together with Maechi Chandra, and in 1970, they started their own temple in [[Pathum Thani]] province, later called Wat Phra Dhammakaya.
The temple became extremely popular in the 1980s. However, from the [[1997 Asian financial crisis]] onward, the temple and Luang Por Dhammajayo came under heavy criticism for unorthodox fundraising methods, culminating in several charges against him. The charges were withdrawn in 2006, and Luang Por Dhammajayo revived the temple. He organized several notable activities in this period, including a campaign against smoking and drinking for which he was rewarded by the [[World Health Organization]].
After the [[2014 Thai coup d'état|2014 coup d'etat]], Luang Por Dhammajayo again was charged by the Thai government, by then a [[Military dictatorship|military junta]], for conspiring in money-laundering and receiving stolen goods. These charges have been widely described as politically motivated, but did lead to an arrest warrant and highly publicized standoff in 2016. The junta was, however, unable to find Luang Por Dhammajayo. As of December 2017, the whereabouts of Luang Por Dhammajayo was still unknown, with Phrakhru Sangharak Rangsarit being assigned as official abbot instead.
== Biography == === Early life and background === Luang Por Dhammajayo was born in [[Sing Buri Province]] with the lay name Chaiyabun Sutthiphon on 22 April 1944, to Janyong Sutthiphon (his father) and Juri Sutthiphon (his mother).{{sfn |Tawandhamma Foundation |2007 |p=20}} His parents were [[Lao Song]] and [[Thai-Chinese]], and separated when he was young. Chaiyabun was raised by his father, who was an engineer working for a government agency.{{sfn |Taylor |1989}}{{sfn |Fuengfusakul |1998 |p=33}} Due to a sensitivity for sunlight, Chaiyabun had to wear sunglasses from a young age.{{sfn |Dhammakaya Foundation |2005 |p=83}}
In Wat Phra Dhammakaya's publications, Chaiyabun is described as a courageous child, who would often play dangerous games with his friends.{{sfn |Fuengfusakul |1998 |p=33}} Whilst studying at [[Suankularb Wittayalai School|Suankularb Wittayalai]], the owner of the school would bring Chaiyabun to meet with monks regularly. This sparked his interest in Buddhism from a young age. He set up a Buddhist Youth Society together with his fellow students.{{sfn |Tawandhamma Foundation |2007 |pp=24–7}}<ref>{{cite book|author=Dhammakaya Foundation|year=2010|title=World Peace Lies Within|location=Bangkok|publisher=Mark Standen Publishing |p=48}}</ref> Chaiyabun developed a strong interest in reading at a young age, especially on Buddhist practice and biographies of leading people in the world, both religious and political.{{sfn |Fuengfusakul |1998 |p=33}}<ref name="Dokbia 991220">{{cite news|script-title=ความไม่ชอบมาพากล กรณีสั่งพักตำแน่งเจ้าอาวาสวัดพระธรรมกาย|trans-title=Suspicious: the case of the removal of Wat Phra Dhammakaya's abbot|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|accessdate=15 December 2016|work=Dokbia Thurakit|date=20 December 1999|page=8|language=th}}</ref> This included a book with teachings from [[Luang Pu Sodh Candasaro]], the founder of the [[Dhammakaya Tradition]], and a magazine about the ''[[maechi]]'' (nun) [[Chandra Khonnokyoong]].{{sfn |Tawandhamma Foundation |2007 }}
In 1963, while studying economics at [[Kasetsart University]], he started visiting the temple [[Wat Paknam Bhasicharoen]]. It was here that he first met Maechi Chandra, a student of abbot Luang Pu Sodh Candasaro, who had by then died.<ref>{{Cite book|author1=[[Dhammakaya Foundation]]|title=The Life & Times of Luang Phaw Wat Paknam|date=1996|publisher=[[Dhammakaya Foundation]]|location=Bangkok|isbn=978-974-89409-4-6|url=http://en.dhammakayapost.org/download/book/02-The-Life-Times-Luang-Phaw-Wat-Paknam.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160419234023/http://en.dhammakayapost.org/download/book/02-The-Life-Times-Luang-Phaw-Wat-Paknam.pdf|dead-url=yes|archive-date=19 April 2016|p=106}}</ref> Maechi Chandra was able to answer Chaiyabun's questions, which made him curious to learn more about Buddhism, through the practice of meditation. Under Maechi Chandra's supervision, Chaiyabun attained a deeper understanding of Buddhism.{{sfn |Tawandhamma Foundation |2007 |pp=32–7}}
Chaiyabun got to know many fellow students both in Kasetsart University and in other universities who were interested in practicing meditation, and encouraged them to join him in learning meditation with Maechi Chandra.{{sfn|McDaniel|2006|p=111}}<ref name="Dokbia 991220" /> One of these early acquaintances later became a Buddhist monk and Luang Por Dhammajayo's assistant: Phadet Phongsawat, now known as [[Luang Por Dattajivo]], who would become the deputy abbot of Wat Phra Dhammakaya. When Chaiyabun met Phadet, Phadet was involved in occult practices ({{lang-th|ไสยศาสตร์}}), and would often hold public demonstrations of such practices for his fellow students. In Wat Phra Dhammakaya's biographies it is told that every time Chaiyabun joined to watch one of Phadet's demonstrations, Phadet was incapable of doing his performance. Phadet therefore become curious about Chaiyabun, suspecting that Chaiyabun was affecting his occult demonstrations. Later on, when Phadet tried to persuade Chaiyabun to drink alcohol at a college party, Chaiyabun refused, citing his adherence to the [[five precepts|five Buddhist precepts]]. To test Chaiyabun, Phadet then decided to bring him to his occult black magic teacher. However, even the teacher could not use his powers in Chaiyabun's presence, which convinced Phadet to learn more about Dhammakaya meditation from Chaiyabun. From that moment on, they remained friends and Phadet became Chaiyabun's assistant.{{sfn |Fuengfusakul |1998 |p=33}}{{sfn |Mackenzie |2007 |pp=40–1}}{{sfn |Litalien |2010 |p=132}}
=== Ordination as monk === During his university years, Chaiyabun wanted to stop his studies to ordain as a monk. However, Maechi Chandra and Chaiyabun's father persuaded him to finish his degree first. They argued that Chaiyabun could do more benefit to society if he was both knowledgeable in mundane and spiritual matters. During university, he took a lifelong vow of celibacy as a birthday gift to Maechi Chandra, inspiring many of her students to do the same.{{sfn |Fuengfusakul |1998 |p=35}} After his graduation from Kasetsart University, he was ordained at Wat Paknam Bhasicharoen on 27 August 1969. He received the [[monastic name]] "Dhammajayo", meaning 'The victor through [[Dhamma]]'.<ref name="Dokbia 1999">{{cite news|script-title=ธรรมกาย..."เรา คือ ผู้บริสุทธิ์" ผู้ใดเห็นธรรม ผู้นั้นเห็นเราตถาคต|trans-title=Dhammakaya: "We are innocent.", "He who sees the Dhamma, sees me, the Tathagata"|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|accessdate=12 December 2016|work=Dokbia Thurakit|date=15 March 1999|page=5|language=th|via=Matichon E-library|url-access=registration}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Rajakaruna|first1=J.|title=Maha Dhammakaya Cetiya where millions congregate seeking inner peace|url=http://archives.dailynews.lk/2008/02/20/fea07.asp|work=[[Daily News (Sri Lanka)]]|publisher=Lake House|date=28 February 2008}}</ref> At his ordination, Phra (meaning 'monk, venerable') Dhammajayo took a vow that he would work to bring progress to Buddhism.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://prachatai.com/journal/2017/02/7033|work=[[Prachatai]]|date=28 February 2017|access-date=24 December 2017|first=Suthachai|last=Yimprasert|script-title=ธรรมกายในประวัติศาสตร์|language=th|trans-title=Dhammakaya in history|publisher=Foundation for Community Studies}}</ref> A university degree in the Thailand of the 1960s could lead to a good job and social standing, making Chaiyabun's decision to ordain uncommon.<ref name="Dokbia 1999" />
Once ordained, he started teaching Dhammakaya meditation together with Maechi Chandra. In the beginning, the meditation courses were carried in a small house called 'Ban Thammaprasit' in the Wat Paknam Bhasicharoen compound. Because of the popularity of both teachers, the house soon became overcrowded with interested students and they considered it more appropriate to start a new center by themselves.<ref name="Thai Post 1998">{{cite news|date=6 December 1998|work=[[Thai Post]]|script-title=เส้นทางพระธรรมกาย|trans-title=The path of Wat Phra Dhammakaya|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|via=Matichon E-library|url-access=registration}}</ref>{{sfn |Fuengfusakul |1998 }} Although initially they intended to buy a plot of land in Patum Thani, the landowner ''[[Khunying]]'' Prayat Suntharawet gave a plot four times the requested size to celebrate her birthday. Thus, on 20 February 1970, Maechi Chandra, Phra Dhammajayo, Phra Dattajivo and their students moved to the 196 ''[[Rai (area)|rai]]'' (313,600&nbsp;m<sup>2</sup>) plot of land to found a meditation center.<ref name="Thai Post 1998" />{{sfn|Sirikanchana|2010}} A book about the initiative was compiled, to inspire people to join in and help with the building of the meditation center.{{sfn |Dhammakaya Foundation |2005 |pp=102–3}} The site eventually became an official temple in 1977 and was later named Wat Phra Dhammakaya.{{sfn |Tawandhamma Foundation |2007 |p=48}}
=== Life as abbot === {{See also|Wat Phra Dhammakaya|History of Wat Phra Dhammakaya}} [[File:Dhammakaya ordination ceremony 2.jpg|link=[[:File:Dhammakaya ordination ceremony 2]].jpg|thumb|Ordination ceremony for new monks at Wat Phra Dhammakaya]] Phra Dhammajayo later became abbot of the temple and was called Luang Por (meaning 'venerable father') Dhammajayo from then on.{{sfn|Mackenzie|2007}} In the early years, Maechi Chandra still had an important role in fundraising and decision-making. However in years to follow, this would gradually become less, as she grew older and withdrew more to the background of the temple's organization. From then onward, Luang Por Dhammajayo received a greater role.{{sfn |Fuengfusakul |1998 |pp=41–3}} The temple gained great popularity during the 1980s (during the [[late 20th century Asian economic boom|Asian economic boom]]),<ref name="Falk 2007">{{cite book|title=Making fields of merit: Buddhist female ascetics and gendered orders in Thailand|last1=Falk|first1=Monica Lindberg|date=2007|publisher=[[Nordic Centre in Shanghai|NIAS Press]]|isbn=978-87-7694-019-5|location=Copenhagen}}</ref>{{sfn|McDaniel|2010|pp=41, 662}}{{sfn|Bechert|1997|p=176}} attracting up to fifty thousand people on major ceremonies.{{sfn|Zehner|2013|p=191}}
In the wake of the [[1997 Asian financial crisis|1997 Asian Financial Crisis]], Wat Phra Dhammakaya and Luang Por Dhammajayo came under widespread criticism and an [[History of Wat Phra Dhammakaya#Investigations and lawsuits|investigation]] from the [[Sangha Supreme Council]]. The main criticism was that the temple was using fundraising methods that did not fit in with Buddhism.{{sfn|Harvey|2013|p=391}}{{sfn|Scott|2009|pp=132–4}}<ref name="Matichon 2006">{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|date=23 August 2006|work=Matichon|accessdate=18 December 2016|page=16|language=th|script-title=ย้อนรอยคดีธัมมชโย|trans-title=Review of Dhammajayo's lawsuits|via=Matichon E-library|url-access=registration}}</ref> One of the accusations investigated was that Luang Por Dhammajayo had moved land donated to the temple to his own name.{{sfn|Scott|2009|pp=129, 137, 143}}<ref name="Thai PBS 1507222">{{cite news|url=http://program.thaipbs.or.th/watch/JUTeqF|last=Chinmani|first=Vorawit|date=22 July 2015|work=[[Thai PBS]]|language=th|script-title=เคลียร์ "คำวินิจฉัย" ปาราชิก|trans-title=Clearing up the analysis of an offense leading to disrobing|episode=1}}</ref> The temple denied this, stating that it was the intention of the donors to give the land to the abbot and not the temple.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://en.dhammakaya.net/frequently-asked-questions/|title=Frequently Asked Questions|publisher=Dhammakaya Foundation|access-date=12 November 2016}}</ref><ref name="Matichon 2006" /> During this time, a letter with the then [[Supreme Patriarch of Thailand|Supreme Patriarch's]] signature was leaked to the press implying that Luang Por Dhammajayo had to disrobe for not returning the land.{{Refn|The consensus was that this was written as a conditional order if (and only if) he did not return the land, which was eventually done.<ref name="Matichon 2015">{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com/|date=23 February 2015|work=Matichon|page=12|language=th|script-title=ฉุนมติมหาเถรสมาคมอุ้มธรรมกาย พุทธะอิสระยกขบวนพรึบวัดปากน้ำ|trans-title=Angered about decision SSC protecting Dhammakaya, Buddha Issara suddenly moves procession to Wat Paknam|via=Matichon E-library|url-access=subscription}}</ref>|group=note}} However, the authenticity of the letter was put into question.{{Refn|Journalists and scholars pointed out some anomalies with the letter, including its layout and the timing of its release. A leading journalist on religious affairs later stated that the Supreme Patriarch would never leak such a letter directly to the press. The then Supreme Patriarch was also seriously ill at the time and could not easily be reached.<ref name="Thai PBS 150723">{{cite news| first=Jirachata|last=Iamrasmi|url=http://program.thaipbs.or.th/watch/moBgUU|work=[[Thai PBS]]|date=23 July 2015|title=เคลียร์ "คำวินิจฉัย" ปาราชิก "พระธัมมชโย"|language=th|trans-title=Clearing up the analysis of an offense leading to disrobing|episode=2}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first1=Jomquan|last=Laopet|script-title=สง(ฆ์)สัยสงฆ์?|trans-title=Is the Sangha in doubt about the Sangha?|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hu0EdHf47eI|accessdate=23 February 2017|work=[[Kom Chad Luek]]|publisher=[[The Nation Group]]|date=23 February 2015|time=18:37|language=th}}</ref>|group=note}}<ref name="Puengnet 19992">{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com/|last1=Puengnet|first1=Pakorn|date=10 December 1999|work=ฺ Bangkok Biz News|accessdate=18 December 2016|publisher=[[The Nation Group]]|page=2|language=th|script-title=ลำดับเหตุการณ์สงฆ์จัดการสงฆ์ 1 ปีแค่พักตำแหน่งธัมมชโย|trans-title=Timeline of events: Sangha dealing with Sangha, after 1 year only suspension for Dhammajayo|via=Matichon E-library|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://program.thaipbs.or.th/watch/pxBoz8|date=18 December 2016|work=[[Thai PBS]]|accessdate=18 December 2016|language=th|script-title=พระสังฆราชองค์ที่ ๒๐|trans-title=The 20th Sangharaja|time=9:12}}</ref> Eventually the Sangha Council declared that Luang Por Dhammajayo had not broken any serious offenses against monastic discipline (''[[Vinaya]]'').<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://opac.mbu.ac.th/Record/3070|title=วิเคราะห์นิคหกรรม ธรรมกาย|last=Udomsi|first=Sawaeng|year=2000|isbn=974-7078-11-2|location=Bangkok|pages=81–5|language=th|trans-title=Analysis of Disciplinary Transactions of Dhammakaya|chapter=รายงานการพิจารณาดำเนินการ กรณีวัดพระธรรมกาย ตามมติมหาเถรสมาคม ครั้งที่ ๓๒/๒๕๔๑|trans-chapter=Report of Evaluation of the Treatment of the Case Wat Phra Dhammakaya-Verdict of the Supreme Sangha Council 32/2541 B.E.}}</ref> Despite this, the {{ill|Religious Affairs Department|th|กรมการศาสนา}} charged Luang Por Dhammajayo with embezzlement and removed him from his post as abbot.<ref name="AP 991007">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1309&dat=19991007&id=cOROAAAAIBAJ&sjid=fxQEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6903,2508411|title=Thai monk to stand down from temple duties|date=7 October 1999|work=[[New Straits Times]]|accessdate=10 November 2016|agency=[[The Associated Press]]|issue=413/12/99|page=19}}</ref>{{sfn |Scott |2009 |p=139}}{{sfn |Mackenzie |2007 |pp=53–4}}
During this period, many Thai news reporters used pejorative language in describing Luang Por Dhammajayo, as well as members of the [[Sangha Supreme Council]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|title=เจ้าคณะปทุมธานียันปลดแน่ ไอ้แว่นกันถอนเงิน|date=14 November 1999|work=[[Khao Sod]]|accessdate=6 December 2016|publisher=Matichon Publishing|page=1|language=th|via=Matichon E-library|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|date=28 May 1999|work=[[Thai Rath]]|accessdate=6 December 2016|publisher=Wacharapol|page=14|language=th|script-title=สมเด็จปากน้ำไม่เข้าคนผิด|trans-title=The Patriarch of Wat Paknam is not favored to the guilty|via=Matichon E-library|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Monastic chiefs nationwide sent letters to the Prime Minister over concerns about the media's language toward the Sangha.<ref name=":0">{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|date=28 May 1999|work=[[Thai Rath]]|accessdate=6 December 2016|publisher=Wacharapol|page=14|language=th|script-title=สมเด็จปากน้ำไม่เข้าคนผิด|trans-title=The Patriarch of Wat Paknam is not favored to the guilty|via=Matichon E-library|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Widespread negative media coverage at this time was symptomatic of the temple being made the [[scapegoat]] for commercial malpractice in the Thai Buddhist temple community.<ref>Julian Gearing (1999) Buddhist Scapegoat?: One Thai abbot is taken to task, but the whole system is to blame ''Asiaweek'' 30 December 1999 [http://www-cgi.cnn.com/ASIANOW/asiaweek/intelligence/9912/30/ {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090625164034/http://www-cgi.cnn.com/ASIANOW/asiaweek/intelligence/9912/30/|date=2009-06-25}}<</ref> In 1999, Wat Phra Dhammakaya filed several successful slander suits against various news outlets.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|title=Dhammakaya to file suits against media|date=8 December 1999|work=[[The Nation (Thailand)]]|page=7|via=Matichon E-library|url-access=subscription}}</ref>{{sfn|Naew Na, 8 December 1999|p=1}}<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dhammakaya.net/blog/2001/09/16/กรณีวัดพระธรรมกาย-1|date=16 September 2001|work=Siam Rath|access-date=1 May 2016|script-title=ประกาศ|trans-title=Announcement|via=dhammakaya.net}}</ref> In an interview held in the same year, LP Dhammajayo stated he understood the government's anxiety about Buddhist movements with large gatherings, but still felt perplexed about the controversies.<ref name="Times Asia article" />{{sfn|Matichon, 10 January 1999|p=4}}[[File:Luang Por Dhammajayo with honnorific fan, sitting in Ubosoth.jpg|thumb|Luang Por Dhammajayo sitting in the [[Ubosot]] at [[Wat Phra Dhammakaya]].]] In the 2000s, Luang Por Dhammajayo began a nationwide anti-smoking and drinking campaign.{{sfn |Zehner |1990 |p=424}}<ref>{{cite journal|author=Scupin, Raymond|year=2001|title=Parallels Between Buddhist and Islamic Movements in Thailand|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/273456943|journal=Prajna Vihara|volume=2|issue=1}}</ref> This project led the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) to present him with a [[World No Tobacco Day]] award in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.who.int/tobacco/communications/events/wntd/2004/awards/en/index5.html|title=WHO–List of World No Tobacco Day awardees–2004|date=17 September 2011|website=[[World Health Organization]]|accessdate=9 January 2016}}</ref>{{sfn|Mackenzie|2007|p=71}}{{sfn |Seeger |2006}} In 2005, over one hundred religious organizations joined the campaign and successfully stopped the listing of liquor company [[Thai Beverages|Thai Beverage]] on the [[Stock Exchange of Thailand]], which would have been the biggest listing in Thai history.<ref name="Hills 2005">{{cite news|last1=Hills|first1=Jonathan|title=CSR and the alcohol industry: a case study from Thailand|url=http://csr-asia.com/csr-asia-weekly-news-detail.php?id=3547|accessdate=29 November 2016|work=CSR Asia|date=5 April 2005|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161129153130/http://csr-asia.com/csr-asia-weekly-news-detail.php?id=3547|archivedate=29 November 2016|df=}}</ref><ref name="Inbaraj 2005">{{cite news|url=http://www.ipsnews.net/2005/03/thailand-beer-and-buddhism-a-definite-no-cry-conservatives/|title=Thailand: Beer and Buddhism, a Definite No, Cry Conservatives|last1=Inbaraj|first1=Sonny|date=20 March 2005|work=[[Inter Press Service]]|accessdate=29 November 2016}}</ref><ref name="Weekend 2005">{{cite news|url=http://www.nationweekend.com/weekend/20050304/web01.shtml|date=4 March 2005|work=Nation Weekend|accessdate=28 November 2016|publisher=[[The Nation Group]]|language=th|script-title=ขบวนการต้านน้ำเมา ร้อยบุปผาบานพร้อมพรัก ร้อยสำนักประชันเพื่อใคร?|trans-title=Resistance against alcohol: a hundred flowers bloom fully, and for who do a hundred institutions compete?}}</ref>
In 2006, the running lawsuits against Luang Por Dhammajayo [[History of Wat Phra Dhammakaya#Charges withdrawn|were withdrawn]] by the Attorney-General, citing that Luang Por Dhammajayo had moved all of the disputed land to the name of the temple and that continuing the case would not benefit the public. His position as abbot was subsequently restored.<ref name="Naew Na 2006">{{cite news|script-title=อัยการถอนฟ้องธัมมชโย ยอมคืนเงินยักยอก 950 ล.|trans-title=Prosecutor withdraws charges Dhammajayo, Dhammajayo agrees to return embezzled 950 M.|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|accessdate=6 December 2016|work=Naew Na|date=23 August 2006|page=1|language=th|via=Matichon E-library|url-access=registration}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Thai court spares founder of Dhammakaya|url=http://www.buddhistchannel.tv/index.php?id=52,3073,0,0,1,0#.VyYxl_l9670|accessdate=11 September 2016|work=[[Bangkok Post]]|via=The Buddhist Channel|date=23 August 2006}}</ref> Five years later, Luang Por Dhammajayo stepped down as abbot of Wat Phra Dhammakaya, with [[Luang Por Dattajivo]] taking over as caretaker abbot, although this was not widely known at the time.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YfqVK9_HSQo|date=9 July 2016|work=[[The Nation (Thailand)]]|accessdate=18 November 2016|language=th|script-title=ตั้งรักษาการเจ้าอาวาสธรรมกาย|trans-title=Acting abbot Dhammakaya appointed}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.voicetv.co.th/thailand/387648.html|last=Kanha|first=Wiranan|date=11 July 2016|work=[[Voice TV]]|access-date=9 February 2017|publisher=Digital TV Network|language=th|script-title=ไม่ใช่ครั้งแรก! ตั้งรักษาการแทนเจ้าอาวาสวัดพระธรรมกาย|trans-title=Not the first time! Acting abbot Wat Phra Dhammakaya appointed}}</ref>
==== Since the 2014 coup d'état ==== New investigations against Luang Por Dhammajayo appeared following the [[2014 Thai coup d'état]]. The [[National Council for Peace and Order|military junta]] created a National Reform Council with a religious committee led by former senator {{ill|Paiboon Nititawan|th|ไพบูลย์ นิติตะวัน}}, {{ill|Phra Suwit Dhiradhammo|th|พระสุวิทย์ ธีรธมฺโม}} (known under the activist name Phra Buddha Issara), and former Wat Phra Dhammakaya monk [[Mano Laohavanich]].<ref name="Dubus 2016">{{cite news|url=http://eglasie.mepasie.org/asie-du-sud-est/thailande/2016-06-22-derriere-la-controverse-autour-du-temple-bouddhique-dhammakaya-un-bras-de-fer-religieux-et-politique|title=Controverse autour du temple bouddhique Dhammakaya: un bras de fer religieux et politique|last=Dubus|first=Arnaud|date=22 June 2016|work=Églises d'Asie|publisher=Information Agency for Foreign Missions of Paris|language=fr|trans-title=Controversy regarding the Dhammakaya Buddhist temple: A religious and political standoff}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Tan Hui Yee|title=Tense times for Thai junta, Buddhist clergy|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/tense-times-for-thai-junta-buddhist-clergy|accessdate=16 November 2016|work=[[The Straits Times]]|publisher=[[Singapore Press Holdings]]|date=25 February 2016|url-access=limited}}</ref><ref name="Tawisak 2016">{{cite news|url=http://www.posttoday.com/analysis/interview/436236|last1=Panichkul|first1=Intarachai|date=8 June 2016|work=Post Today|accessdate=3 December 2016|publisher=The Post Publishing|language=th|script-title=วิพากษ์ "ปรากฎการณ์โค่นธรรมกาย" สุรพศ ทวีศักดิ์|trans-title=Surapot Tawisak: commenting on the fall of Dhammakaya}}</ref> In February 2015, Paiboon Nititawan led an unsuccessful bid to reopen the alleged land embezzlement case against Luang Por Dhammajayo from 1999.<ref name="Dubus 2016" /><ref name="Piyanuch 2015">{{cite news|url=http://news.asiaone.com/news/asia/thai-abbot-be-probed-over-massive-donations|title=Thai abbot to be probed over massive donations|work=[[The Nation (Thailand)]]|via=Asia One|agency=[[Asia News Network]]|last=Thamnukasetchai|first=Piyanuch|date=28 February 2015}}</ref> Meanwhile, Phra Suwit requested the [[Department of Special Investigation]] (DSI) to start an investigation in the assets of the Sangha Council's members. This included [[Somdet Chuang Varapuñño]], who was Luang Por Dhammajayo's preceptor (the person who ordained him).<ref name="Dubus 20162">{{cite news|url=http://eglasie.mepasie.org/asie-du-sud-est/thailande/2016-06-22-derriere-la-controverse-autour-du-temple-bouddhique-dhammakaya-un-bras-de-fer-religieux-et-politique|title=Controverse autour du temple bouddhique Dhammakaya: un bras de fer religieux et politique|last=Dubus|first=Arnaud|date=22 June 2016|work=Églises d'Asie|publisher=Information Agency for Foreign Missions of Paris|language=fr|trans-title=Controversy regarding the Dhammakaya Buddhist temple: A religious and political standoff}}</ref><ref name="Dubus 201601182">{{cite news|url=http://eglasie.mepasie.org/asie-du-sud-est/thailande/2016-01-18-la-thailande-se-dechire-a-propos-de-la-nomination-du-chef-des-bouddhistes/|title=La Thaïlande se déchire à propos de la nomination du chef des bouddhistes|last=Dubus|first=Arnaud|date=18 January 2016|work=Églises d'Asie|publisher=Information Agency for Foreign Missions of Paris|language=fr|trans-title=Thailand is torn about the appointment of a Buddhist leader}}</ref>
In 2015, Luang Por Dhammajayo was implicated in the [[History of Wat Phra Dhammakaya#Klongchan controversy|Klongchan Credit Union controversy]] when 11.37 billion [[Thai baht|baht]] was taken out of the Klongchan Credit Union Cooperative (KCUC) via unauthorized checks, in which a portion totaling more than a billion baht were found to have been given to Wat Phra Dhammakaya via donations. In defense, spokespeople of Wat Phra Dhammakaya explained that Luang Por Dhammajayo was not aware that the donations were illegally obtained.<ref name="Yee 161116">{{cite news|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/opinion/politics-and-religion-coming-worryingly-together-in-temple-scandal|title=Politics and religion coming worryingly together in temple scandal|author=Tan Hui Yee|date=23 June 2016|work=[[The Straits Times]]|accessdate=16 November 2016|publisher=[[Singapore Press Holdings]]|url-access=limited}}</ref><ref name="Thai PBS 1605022">{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=s72K_zUt5T0|title=|last=|first=|date=2 May 2016|work=[[Thai PBS]]|accessdate=11 November 2016|publisher=|language=th|script-title=พิษเงินบริจาคพันล้าน|trans-title=Poisonous donations of a billion baht|lay-url=http://www.dhammakayauncovered.com/editorial/2016/4/21/a-perspective-on-the-klongchan-credit-union-cooperative-case|lay-source=Dhammakaya Uncovered|lay-date=21 April 2016|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.springnews.co.th/program/newstalk/facetime/289026|title=|last=|first=|date=28 April 2016|work=[[Spring News]]|accessdate=4 April 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160502103703/http://www.springnews.co.th/program/newstalk/facetime/289026|archivedate=2 May 2016|deadurl=yes|publisher=|language=th|script-title=ฟังทนายพระธัมมชโย แจงคดีร้อน|trans-title=Let's listen to the lawyer of Phra Dhammajayo, providing information about a controversial lawsuit|lay-url=http://www.dhammakayauncovered.com/editorial/2016/4/21/a-perspective-on-the-klongchan-credit-union-cooperative-case|lay-source=Dhammakaya Uncovered|lay-date=21 April 2016|via=|df=}}</ref> In a written agreement with the credit union, supporters of the temple had raised the money linked to Wat Phra Dhammakaya to donate to the KCUC to compensate their members.<ref name="Thai PBS 1605022" />
Regardless, Luang Por Dhammajayo was summoned to acknowledge the charges of ill-gotten gains and conspiring to money-laundering at the offices of the DSI.<ref name="Thai PBS 160502">{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=s72K_zUt5T0|title=|last=|first=|date=2 May 2016|work=[[Thai PBS]]|accessdate=11 November 2016|publisher=|language=th|script-title=พิษเงินบริจาคพันล้าน|trans-title=Poisonous donations of a billion baht|lay-url=http://www.dhammakayauncovered.com/editorial/2016/4/21/a-perspective-on-the-klongchan-credit-union-cooperative-case|lay-source=Dhammakaya Uncovered|lay-date=21 April 2016|via=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.aparchive.com/metadata/Thailand-Temple/f1de88b4d2b46d648fcc53eeaec5a425|title=Police raid Thai temple in search of wanted monk|date=16 June 2016|work=[[Thai PBS]]|via=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref><ref name="Constant 161115">{{cite news|url=http://aa.com.tr/en/asia-pacific/thai-police-blocked-from-arresting-controversial-abbot/590527|title=Thai police blocked from arresting controversial abbot|work=[[Anadolu Agency]]|last2=Constant|first2=Max|location=Bangkok|last1=Thana|first1=CS|accessdate=15 November 2016}}</ref> The temple requested the DSI to let him acknowledge his charges at the temple due to his [[deep vein thrombosis]], a request the DSI refused.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2x6ovTnf0nQ|title=|last=|first=|date=27 May 2016|work=Thai News Network|accessdate=9 August 2016|language=th|script-title=ย้อนหลัง สนง.คดีอาญาเผย DSI จะส่งพระธัมมชโยฟ้องศาลไม่ได้หากคดีไม่มีมูล|trans-title=Review: Office of Criminal Law states DSI cannot charge Phra Dhammajayo if lawsuit is baseless|quote=Subtitled [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wd-oHil2MFU here]|via=Bright TV}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=เสียงเสรี SEREE VOICE|title=ฉบับเฉพาะตอน ทุจริต อผศ.และกรณีพระธัมมชโย|date=24 June 2016|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zCQIWfqtc48|accessdate=23 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Thai News Network|title=Interview of Mr.Paramat Intarachumum|date=1 June 2016|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?time_continue=1&v=wd-oHil2MFU|accessdate=18 February 2018}}</ref> When Luang Por Dhammajayo failed to appear at the DSI office to acknowledge his charges, authorities launched several failed raids of the temple to find him.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/archive/monks-summoned-for-questioning-in-dhammajayo-case/1029061|title=Monks summoned for questioning in Dhammajayo's case|date=6 July 2016|work=[[Bangkok Post]]|publisher=The Post Publishing|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nationmultimedia.com/news/national/30293565|title=Dhammakaya lawyer, M-home board members hear charges|last1=Tamnukasetchai|first1=Piyanuch|date=23 August 2016|work=[[The Nation (Thailand)]]|accessdate=16 November 2016}}</ref> The standoff led to a [[History of Wat Phra Dhammakaya#Junta's lockdown|23-day lockdown]] of the temple in 2017 by the junta using [[Prayut Chan-o-cha#Article 44|Article 44]] of the [[2014 interim constitution of Thailand|interim constitution]], despite the efforts authorities were still unable to find him.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.voanews.com/a/thai-authorities-contine-standoff-at-buddhist-temple/3743269.html|title=Thai Authorities Continue Standoff at Buddhist Temple|last=Corben|first=Ron|work=[[VOA]]|access-date=1 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/opinion/opinion/1199953/misguided-section-44-use|title=Misguided Section 44 use|work=[[Bangkok Post]]|access-date=1 March 2017|publisher=Post Publishing}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/opinion/opinion/1208953/dhammakaya-sagas-cost-is-too-high|title=Dhammakaya saga's cost is too high|work=[[Bangkok Post]]|access-date=6 March 2017|publisher=Post Publishing}}</ref> Many reporters questioned the practicality of using Article 44 and so many resources to arrest one person to acknowledge a charge of a non-violent crime, and pointed out the viability of trying him ''[[in absentia]]'' to determine guilt first.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.voanews.com/a/thai-authorities-contine-standoff-at-buddhist-temple/3743269.html|title=Thai Authorities Continue Standoff at Buddhist Temple|last=Corben|first=Ron|work=VOA|access-date=1 March 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/opinion/opinion/1199953/misguided-section-44-use|title=Misguided Section 44 use|last=PCL.|first=Post Publishing|date=|work=Bangkok Post|access-date=1 March 2017}}</ref>
News analysts have speculated that the actions of the Thai junta towards the temple may have reflected a political need to control who should be selected as the next [[Supreme Patriarch of Thailand]]. The monk who was next in line for the position, Somdet Chuang Varapuñño, had ordained Luang Por Dhammajayo.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-thailand-monks-idUKKCN0XJ0CJ|title=Devotees at Thai temple give alms to tens of thousands of Buddhist monks|last=Tanakasempipat|first=Patpicha|date=22 April 2016|work=[[Reuters]]|accessdate=20 August 2016|last2=Kittisilpa|first2=Juarawee|editor-last=Lefevre|editor-first=Amy Sawitta|last3=Thepgumpanat|first3=Panarat}}</ref><ref name="Lok 20172">{{cite news|url=http://www.lokwannee.com/web2013/?p=259415|last=Yimprasert|first=Sutchachai|date=27 February 2017|work=Lok Wan Nee|access-date=13 March 2017|language=th|script-title=ธรรมกายในประวัติศาสตร์|trans-title=The history of Dhammakaya}}</ref>{{refn|Prior to the change in law in December 2016, the Supreme Patriarch was chosen from whoever was the most senior member of the [[Sangha Supreme Council]], who, at the time, was Somdet Chuang.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nationmultimedia.com/news/national/30303058|title=Sangha Act set to pass – The Nation|work=The Nation|access-date=2 May 2018|language=en}}</ref>|group=note}} Selecting Somdet Chuang would have meant a Supreme Patriarch from the [[Maha Nikaya]] fraternity, rather than the [[Dhammayuttika Nikaya|Dhammayuttika]] fraternity, which historically had been the preferred choice by the Thai government and the monarchy.<ref name="Economist 1604022">{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/news/asia/21695901-squabble-clergy-widens-thailands-dangerous-divides-men-alms?fsrc=scn%2Fle%2Fte%2Fpe%2Fed%2Fmenatalms|title=Men-at-alms|date=2 April 2016|work=[[The Economist]]|accessdate=20 August 2016|location=Patumthani}}</ref>{{sfn|McCargo|2012|p=638}} In fact, Somdet Chuang's appointment was withdrawn by the [[National Council for Peace and Order|Thai Junta]], with another candidate from the Dhammayuttika fraternity appointed instead.<ref name="Nation 20172">{{cite news|url=http://www.nationmultimedia.com/news/breakingnews/30305856|title=Somdet Phra Maha Muneewong appointed new supreme patriarch|date=7 February 2017|work=[[The Nation]]|access-date=8 February 2017|url-access=limited}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nationmultimedia.com/news/national/30303058|title=Sangha Act set to pass – The Nation|work=The Nation|access-date=4 September 2017|language=en}}</ref> The coinciding lawsuits against Luang Por Dhammajayo, and Somdet Chuang's connection to him were, in fact, eventually used as a reason by the junta to withdraw his nomination.<ref name="Nation 201722">{{cite news|url=http://www.nationmultimedia.com/news/breakingnews/30305856|title=Somdet Phra Maha Muneewong appointed new supreme patriarch|date=7 February 2017|work=[[The Nation]]|access-date=8 February 2017|url-access=limited}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nationmultimedia.com/news/national/30303058|title=Sangha Act set to pass – The Nation|work=The Nation|access-date=4 September 2017|language=en}}</ref>
In the [[History of Wat Phra Dhammakaya#Aftermath and revival|aftermath]] of the lockdown additional charges were filed, this time also against the deputy abbot, [[Luang Por Dattajivo]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nationmultimedia.com/news/national/30309353|title=Temple money "invested in shares"|work=[[The Nation]]|access-date=24 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=":22">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-thailand-buddhism-idUSKBN16U0NU|title=Thailand seeks new abbot for scandal-hit Buddhist temple|date=23 March 2017|work=[[Reuters]]|access-date=24 March 2017|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6wzQlSYJW|archive-date=4 February 2018|deadurl=no}}</ref> With both Wat Phra Dhammakaya's honorary and deputy abbot under investigation, the junta pushed unsuccessfully to appoint an "outsider" abbot to run the temple.<ref name=":22" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bangkokpost.com/archive/new-abbot-sought-to-replace-dhammajayo/1219965|title=New abbot sought to replace Dhammajayo|work=[[Bangkok Post]]|archive-url=https://archive.is/rzKVz|archive-date=4 February 2018|deadurl=no|access-date=30 January 2018|}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://englishnews.thaipbs.or.th/buddhism-office-proposes-appointment-new-abbot-dhammakaya-temple/|title=Buddhism Office proposes appointment of new abbot of Dhammakaya temple|date=22 March 2017|work=[[Thai PBS]]|accessdate=4 February 2018}}</ref> The junta stated it was necessary to take over the temple because it is a "threat to national security".<ref name="BBC 20172">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-39263793|title=The curious case of a hidden abbot and a besieged temple|last=Head|first=Jonathan|date=22 March 2017|work=[[BBC]]|accessdate=22 March 2017|location=Bangkok}}</ref><ref name="Reuters 170224">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-thailand-buddhism-power-idUSKBN163037|title=The power struggle behind Thailand's temple row|last1=Tostevin|first1=Matthew|date=24 February 2017|work=[[Reuters]]|accessdate=25 February 2017|last2=Satrusayang|first2=Cod|last3=Thempgumpanat|first3=Panarat}}</ref>
In December 2016, Luang Por Dhammajayo was given the position of honorary abbot by the Ecclesiastical Provincial Chief (governing monk of the region) of Pathum Thani.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bangkokbiznews.com/news/detail/731008|title=ตั้ง 'พระสมบุญ' นั่งรักษาการเจ้าอาวาสธรรมกาย [Phra Somboon to be named acting abbot of Dhammakaya]|last=|first=|date=|work=|newspaper=bangkokbiznews|access-date=9 December 2016|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=th-TH|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.voicetv.co.th/thailand/440064.html|title=เจ้าคณะจ.ปทุมธานี ปลด 'ธัมมชโย' พ้นเจ้าอาวาส วัดพระธรรมกาย|last=Ltd.Thailand|first=VOICE TV|website=VoiceTV|access-date=9 December 2016}}</ref> In December 2017, the temple assigned Phrakhru Sangharak Rangsarit as the temple's new abbot and began announcing the organization of new events. News outlet [[Kom Chad Luek]] described this as a "revival" of the temple, but news outlet [[Thai PBS]] stated that the temple had not been affected much by the disappearance of the former abbot.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?&v=VSQ14hAOHpI|date=14 December 2017|work=[[Kom Chad Luek]]|access-date=24 December 2017|language=th|script-title=ธรรมกายคืนชีพ!|trans-title=Dhammakaya is revived!}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?&v=mTVfbqI5XBs|date=29 November 2017|work=[[Amarin (Thailand)]]|access-date=25 December 2017|language=th|script-title=ความคิดเห็นประชาชนกับกระแสการกลับมาของธุดงค์ธรรมชัยวัดพระธรรมกาย|trans-title=People's opinions about the revival of the Dhammachai Dhutanga of Wat Phra Dhammakaya}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|script-title=ธรรมกายในวันที่ไร้พระธัมมชโย|trans-title=Dhammakaya now without Dhammajayo|url=http://news.thaipbs.or.th/content/268946|accessdate=7 January 2018|work=[[Thai PBS]]|date=29 December 2017|language=th-TH|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180107233018/http://news.thaipbs.or.th/content/268946|archivedate=7 January 2018}}</ref> In 2017, Wat Phra Dhammakaya was described as the largest temple of Thailand.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/world/massed-police-surround-bangkok-buddhist-temple-in-standoff-with-monks-20161227-gtidu4.html|title=Police delay raid on Thailand's largest temple after stand-off with monks|last=Murdoch|first=Lindsay|date=27 December 2016|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|access-date=8 January 2017|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161229210053/http://www.smh.com.au/world/massed-police-surround-bangkok-buddhist-temple-in-standoff-with-monks-20161227-gtidu4.html|archivedate=29 December 2016}}</ref>
== Teachings == Luang Por Dhammajayo's approach to Buddhism seeks to combine the ascetic and meditative life with modern personal ethics and social prosperity.{{sfn |Litalien |2010 |pp=131–2 }} Luang Por Dhammajayo is mostly known for his teachings with regard to Dhammakaya meditation. In his approach to propagating Buddhism he has emphasized a return to a purer Buddhism, as it had been in the past. He has also opposed protective magic and prognostication and refers to these as signs that Buddhism is deteriorating.{{sfn|McDaniel|2006|p=112}} Many followers in the temple believe that his projects are a product of his visions in meditation.{{sfn |Fuengfusakul |1998 |p=34}}
Luang Por Dhammajayo is known for his modern style of temple management and iconography.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Thai Buddhism Today: Crisis? in: Buddhism Into the Year 2000|last=Na Songkhla|first=N.|publisher=[[Dhammakaya Foundation]]|year=1994|isbn=9748920933|location=Khlong Luang, Patumthani|pages=115–6}}</ref> Luang Por Dhammajayo's approach to Buddhism seeks to combine both the ascetic and meditative life, as well as modern personal ethics and social prosperity.{{sfn |Litalien |2010 |pp=131–2}} Luang Por Dhammajayo often uses positive terms to describe [[Nirvana]]. Apart from the [[Anatta#Current disputes|true self]] as taught by the Dhammakaya Movement as a whole, religious studies scholar Rachelle Scott notes that Wat Phra Dhammakaya often describes Nirvana as being the supreme happiness, and argues that this may explain why the practice of Dhammakaya meditation is so popular.{{sfn |Scott |2009 |p=80}} In its teachings on how meditation can help improve health and the quality of modern life, the temple has been compared to the [[Vipassana movement]] of [[Sn goenka|S.N Goenka]].{{sfn |Scott |2009 |p=77}} The temple's emphasis on meditation is expressed in several ways. Meditation books and CDs are for sale in stores around the temple, and every gathering that is organized by the temple will feature some time for meditation.{{sfn|McDaniel|2006}}<ref name="Newell 2008">{{cite thesis|last1=Newell|first1=Catherine Sarah|title=Monks, meditation and missing links: continuity, "orthodoxy" and the vijja dhammakaya in Thai Buddhism|date=1 April 2008|publisher=Department of the Study of Religions, [[School of Oriental and African Studies]], [[University of London]]|location=London|type=Ph.D. |p=242}}</ref> The temple emphasizes the usefulness of meditating in a group, and sociologist Apinya Fuengfusakul notes that public meditations have a powerful effect on the minds of the practitioners.{{sfn |Fuengfusakul |1998 |pp=95–6}}{{sfn |Harvey |2013 |p=389}}
Luang Por Dhammajayo was heavily influenced by Maechi Chandra Khonnokyoong in her teachings. He turned the Dhammakaya meditation method "into an entire guide of living" (McDaniel), emphasizing cleanliness, orderliness, and quiet, as a morality by itself and as a support for meditation.{{sfn |McDaniel |2010 |p=662}}{{sfn |Zehner |1990}}{{sfn |Fuengfusakul |1998 |p=172}} In short, Wat Phra Dhammakaya's appearance is orderly, and can be described as "a contemporary aesthetic" (Scott), which appeals to practitioners, especially the modern [[Bangkok]] middle class.<ref name="bun">{{cite journal|last1=Bunbongkarn|first1=Suchit|title=Thailand: Farewell to Old–Style Politics?|journal=Southeast Asian Affairs|date=1 January 2000|pages=285–95|jstor=27912257|publisher=[[ISEAS]], Yosuf Ishak Institute}}</ref>{{sfn |Zehner |2013 |page=192}}{{sfn |Scott |2009 |p=56}} Practitioners are also encouraged to keep things tidy and clean, through organized cleaning activities. A strong work ethic is promoted through these activities, in which the most menial work is seen as the most valuable and fruitful.{{sfn |Fuengfusakul |1998 |pp=101–3, 171}}
Wat Phra Dhammakaya has a vision of a [[Utopia|future ideal society]].{{sfn |Taylor |1989 |p=124}} Wat Phra Dhammakaya is known for its emphasis on meditation, especially ''[[samatha]]'' meditation (meditation aiming at tranquility of mind).<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Snodgrass|first1=Judith|date=2003|title=Building Thai Modernity: The Maha Dhammakaya Cetiya|journal=Architectural Theory Review|volume=8|issue=2|doi=10.1080/13264820309478494}}</ref><ref>{{cite encyclopedia|year=1991|title=Fundamentalistic Movements in Theravada Buddhism|encyclopedia=Fundamentalisms Observed|publisher=[[University of Chicago Press]]|location=Chicago; London|last=Swearer|first=Donald K.|series=[[The Fundamentalism Project]]|volume=1|editor-last1=Marty|editor-first1=M.E.|editor-link1=Martin E. Marty|editor-last2=Appleby|editor-first2=R.S. |p=661}}</ref> Through Luang Por Dhammajayo's teachings, Wat Phra Dhammakaya started to develop a more international approach to its teachings, teaching meditation in non-Buddhist countries as a religiously neutral technique suitable for those of all faiths, or none.{{sfn |Mackenzie |2007 |pp=48, 63, 71}}<ref name="Newell 2008" /> The temple emphasizes that the daily application of Buddhism will lead the practitioner and society to prosperity and happiness in this life and the next, and the temple expects a high commitment to that effect.{{sfn |Taylor |1989 |p=123}} Through meditation, fundraising activities and volunteer work, the temple emphasizes the making of merit,{{sfn |Seeger |2006 |p=7}}{{sfn |Scott |2009 |pp=55, 92}} and explains how through the [[Karma in Buddhism|law of kamma]] merit yields its fruits, in this world and the next.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia| title=Dhammakāya Movement | encyclopedia=Encyclopedia of Religion | publisher=[[Thomson Gale]]| last=Zehner|first=Edwin| editor-last=Jones|editor-first=Lindsay | year=2005 | volume=4 | edition=2 | location=Farmington Hills|page=2325}}</ref>{{sfn |Fuengfusakul |1998 |p=167}} The ideal of giving as a form of building character is expressed in the temple's culture with the words ''Cittam me'', meaning 'I am victorious', referring to the overcoming of inner defilements (''{{lang-pi|kilesa}}'').<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.matichonelibrary.com|title=|last=|first=|date=28 June 1999|work=Matichon|script-title=ธรรมกายดิ้นดูดลูกค้า ตั้งรางวัลเพิ่มสมาชิกกัลยาณมิตร|trans-title=Dhammakaya struggles and attracts customers, announces prize for finding more ''kalyanamitta'' members|access-date=1 November 2016|via=Matichon E-library|url-access=registration}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2MBQm2zlPCI|title=|date=2 June 2016|work=Amarin TV|language=th|script-title=สอนธรรมโดยธัมมชโย อวดอุตริ?|trans-title=Dhammachayo's Dhamma teaching: claiming superior human states?|via=|last1=Aphiwan|first1=Phuttha|accessdate=20 November 2016}}</ref>
== Recognition == In 1994, LP Dhammajayo received an honorary degree from the [[Mahachulalongkornrajavidyalaya University]].{{sfn |Fuengfusakul |1998 |pp=123{{en dash}}4}}{{sfn |Litalien |2010 |p=131}} In 2013, in commemoration of year 2550 of the [[Buddhist Era]], the World Buddhist Sangha Youth (WBSY) presented the Universal Peace Award to LP Dhammajayo at the third WBSY meeting in recognition of his work in disseminating Buddhism for more than thirty years.{{sfn |Seeger |2006 |p=11}}<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=HiVoq_OHit4C|title=Buddhism and Postmodern Imaginings in Thailand: The Religiosity of Urban Space|date=2008|publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd.|isbn=978-0-7546-6247-1|last1=Taylor|first1=Jim|accessdate=18 September 2016|p=51}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Taylor|first1=Jim|title=Buddhism, Copying, and the Art of the Imagination in Thailand|journal=Journal of Global Buddhism|date=2007|volume=8}}</ref> Other awards that have been given to LP Dhammajayo are the Phuttha-khunupakan award from the [[House of Representatives (Thailand)|House of Representatives]] in 2009,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kairung|first1=Traithep|script-title=พุทธคุณูปการ โล่เกียรติคุณแด่ผู้ทำคุณต่อพุทธฯ|trans-title=Phuttha-khunupakan: Honorary awards for those who have provided benefit for Buddhism|url=http://www.komchadluek.net/detail/20090429/10915/พุทธคุณูปการโล่เกียรติคุณแด่ผู้ทำคุณต่อพุทธฯ.html|accessdate=15 November 2016|work=[[Kom Chad Luek]]|publisher=Nation Group| date=2009| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120108202248/http://www.komchadluek.net/detail/20090429/10915/%E0%B8%9E%E0%B8%B8%E0%B8%97%E0%B8%98%E0%B8%84%E0%B8%B8%E0%B8%93%E0%B8%B9%E0%B8%9B%E0%B8%81%E0%B8%B2%E0%B8%A3%E0%B9%82%E0%B8%A5%E0%B9%88%E0%B9%80%E0%B8%81%E0%B8%B5%E0%B8%A2%E0%B8%A3%E0%B8%95%E0%B8%B4%E0%B8%84%E0%B8%B8%E0%B8%93%E0%B9%81%E0%B8%94%E0%B9%88%E0%B8%9C%E0%B8%B9%E0%B9%89%E0%B8%97%E0%B8%B3%E0%B8%84%E0%B8%B8%E0%B8%93%E0%B8%95%E0%B9%88%E0%B8%AD%E0%B8%9E%E0%B8%B8%E0%B8%97%E0%B8%98%E0%B8%AF.html|archivedate=8 January 2012|language=th}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|script-title=ถวายรางวัลผู้ทำประโยชน์ต่อพระพุทธศาสนา|language=th|trans-title=Offering rewards for those who have been of benefit to Buddhism|url=http://www2.thairath.co.th/content/edu/1233|accessdate=15 November 2016|work=[[Thai Rath]]|publisher=Vacharaphol Co., Ltd.|date=22 April 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090423024616/http://www2.thairath.co.th/content/edu/1233|archivedate=23 April 2009}}</ref> and a World Buddhist Leader Award from the National Office of Buddhism (2014).<ref>{{cite news|script-title='ธัมมชโย-ติช นัท ฮันห์'รับรางวัล'ผู้นำพุทธโลก'|language=th|trans-title=Dhammajayo and Thich Nhat Hanh receive World Buddhist Leader Awards|url=http://www.komchadluek.net/news/lifestyle/178316#.UvhRx_l_tfW|accessdate=15 November 2016|work=[[Kom Chad Luek]]|publisher=Nation Group|date=5 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|script-title="ธัมมชโย-ติช นัท ฮันห์" รับรางวัล "ผู้นำพุทธโลก"|trans-title=Dhammajayo and Thich Nath Hanh receive World Buddhist Leader Awards|url=http://www.springnews.co.th/newsupdate/78746|accessdate=28 November 2016|work=[[Spring News]]|date=5 February 2014|language=th}}</ref>
Luang Por Dhammajayo was give the [[Ecclesiastical peerage of Thailand|monastic title]] of Phrasudharmayanathera in 1991,<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://www.ratchakitcha.soc.go.th/DATA/PDF/2534/D/213/1.PDF|trans-title=Announcement of Prime Minister's Office Concerning the Offering of Monastic Titles|script-title=ประกาศสำนักนายกรัฐมนตรี เรื่อง พระราชทานสัญญาบัตรตั้งสมณศักดิ์|publisher=The Secretariat of the Cabinet|last=|first=|series=The Royal Gazette|volume=Special Issue Vol.108, Ch. 213|date=12 June 1991|isbn=|location=|page=7}}</ref> followed by Phrarajbhavanavisudh in 1996.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://www.ratchakitcha.soc.go.th/DATA/PDF/2539/B/023/14.PDF|trans-title=Announcement of Prime Minister's Office Concerning the Offering of Monastic Titles|script-title=ประกาศสำนักนายกรัฐมนตรี เรื่อง พระราชทานสัญญาบัตรตั้งสมณศักดิ์|last=|first=|series=The Royal Gazette|volume=Special Issue Vol.113, Ch. 23b|publisher=The Secretariat of the Cabinet|date=5 December 1996|isbn=|location=|page=20}}</ref> In 2011, he received his third and last title Phrathepyanmahamuni.{{sfn |Mackenzie |2007 |pages=40–1}}<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://www.ratchakitcha.soc.go.th/DATA/PDF/2555/B/006/1.PDF|trans-title=Announcement of Prime Minister's Office Concerning the Offering of Monastic Titles |script-title=ประกาศสำนักนายกรัฐมนตรี เรื่อง พระราชทานสัญญาบัตรตั้งสมณศักดิ์|last=|first=|series=The Royal Gazette|volume=Special Issue Vol.129, Ch. 6b|publisher=The Secretariat of the Cabinet|date=15 February 2011|isbn=|location=|pages=2}}</ref> In March 2017, King [[Rama X]] approved a request by junta leader [[Prayuth Chan-ocha]] to remove Luang Por Dhammajayo's title for not acknowledging the charges laid upon him.<ref>{{cite journal|date=5 March 2017|title=ประกาศสำนักนายกรัฐมนตรี เรื่อง ถอดถอนสมณศักดิ์ ลงวันที่ ๕ มีนาคม ๒๕๖๐|trans-title=Announcement of the Office of the Prime Minister on Removal of Ecclesiastical Title dated 5 March 2017|url=http://www.ratchakitcha.soc.go.th/DATA/PDF/2560/B/008/1.PDF|journal=[[Royal Thai Government Gazette]]|language=th|volume=134|issue=8 B|page=1|accessdate=5 March 2017}}</ref>
