'''Nigel Warburton''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|w|ɔr|b|ər|t|ən}}; born 1962) is a British [[philosopher]]. He is best known as a populariser of philosophy, having written a number of books in the genre, but he has also written academic works in [[aesthetics]] and [[applied ethics]].<ref>Baggini, Julian & Jeremy Stangroom (eds.) ''New British Philosophy'', p. 272. Routledge, 2002. {{ISBN|0-415-24346-7}}.</ref>
==Education== Warburton received a [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] from the [[University of Bristol]] and a [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] from [[Darwin College, Cambridge]], and was a lecturer at the [[University of Nottingham]] before joining the Department of Philosophy at [[the Open University]] in 1994.<ref>{{cite web|title=Faculty of Arts: Department of Philosophy|publisher=Open University|url=http://www.open.ac.uk/Arts/philos/warburton.htm|accessdate=2007-09-04}}</ref> In May 2013, he resigned from the position of Senior Lecturer at the Open University.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=The Philosophers Magazine|title=Nigel Warburton, virtual philosopher|url=http://philosophypress.co.uk/?p=1159|accessdate=2013-06-10|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130622022556/http://philosophypress.co.uk/?p=1159|archivedate=2013-06-22|df=}}</ref>
==Career== He is the author of a number of introductory Philosophy books, including the bestselling ''Philosophy: The Basics'' (4th ed.), ''Philosophy: The Classics'' (4th ed.), and ''Thinking from A to Z'' (3rd ed.); he also edited ''Philosophy: Basic Readings'' (2nd ed.) and was the co-author of ''Reading Political Philosophy: Machiavelli to Mill''. He has written extensively about photography, particularly about [[Bill Brandt]], and wrote a biography of the modernist architect [[Ernő Goldfinger]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Nigel Warburton CV at PFD|publisher=PFD Group Ltd|url=http://www.pfd.co.uk/clients/warburtn/b-aut.html|accessdate=2007-09-04 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071024175008/http://www.pfd.co.uk/clients/warburtn/b-aut.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2007-10-24}}</ref> He regularly teaches courses on philosophy and art at [[Tate Modern]] and writes a monthly column "Everyday Philosophy" for ''Prospect'' magazine.
He runs a philosophy [[weblog]] ''Virtual Philosopher''<ref>http://www.virtualphilosopher.org</ref> and with [[David Edmonds (philosopher)|David Edmonds]] regularly podcasts interviews with top philosophers on a range of subjects at ''[[Philosophy Bites]]''.<ref>http://www.philosophybites.com</ref> He also podcasts chapters from his book ''Philosophy: The Classics''.<ref>http://www.philclassics.libsyn.com</ref>
