The '''Stichometry of Nicephorus''' is a [[stichometry]] by [[Patriarch Nicephorus I of Constantinople]]. It is significant in that it counts the number of lines of various Christian texts, many of which have been lost over the course of time. This has enabled modern scholars to determine how much of various fragmentary texts from the [[New Testament apocrypha]] and Old Testament [[apocrypha]] remain missing.
==External links== * [http://www.ntcanon.org/Stichometry_of_Nicephorus.shtml The stichometry of Nicephorus] (English, Greek, Latin) * [https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_mr0UAAAAQAAJ Teubner edition with critical apparatus] in Nikephoros, ''Chronographikon syntomon'' in: Nicephori Archiepiscopi Constantinopolitani, ''Opuscula historica'', ed. C. de Boor, Leipzig 1880, p.&nbsp;80–135, esp. 132 – 135. (Greek, Internet Archive) * [https://archive.org/details/analectakrzeret00preugoog In a collection of documents on the history of the Christian canon] by E. Preuschen, ''Analecta'' (Freiberg and Leipzig: Mohr, 1893), pp.&nbsp;156–8. (Greek, Internet Archive). {{Authority control}} [[Category:Apocrypha]] [[Category:Manuscripts]]
